up. 15. The office of tribunes of the people continued to exist at Rome till the fifth century of our era. Augustus and his successore, however, by assuming it themselves, made the other tribunes comparatively powerless. Tacitus indeed mentions the case of Arulenus Rusticus, in Nero's reign, and of Vulcatius in the first year of Vespasian, showing that the power of ‘interceding' by veto, in the Senam, still remained.
